2. VDOPs and  same sex cases 
With  the  passage  of    AB  2684 (chaptered  9/28/2018), 
many provisions of   the family code were revised, to 
create  a  more  gender-neutral  code.  Indeed,  VDOPs  
are  no  longer  limited  to  unmarried  birth  parents. 
All proposed parents, even married ones and same-
sex couples, may use the VDOP, when the child was 
conceived through assisted reproduction and one of 
the   signing   parties   is   the   birth   parent.   
FC   § 
7573(a)(2) Note:   If   neither   parent   is   the   birth 
parent, the parents may not utilize the VDOP, as that 
process  requires  a  birth  mother.  Same-sex  parents 
not   eligible   for   the   VDOP   may   still   establish   
parentage  by  other  means  including  the  application  
of legal presumptions and/or surrogacy agreements. 
3. Estoppel 
A  pregnant  mother  who  stipulates  to  a  parentage  
judgment  establishing  her  lesbian  partner  as  the  
second  parent  of  her  unborn  child  is  later  estopped  
from   challenging   the   validity   of   the   parentage   
judgment.  (Kristine  H.  v.  Lisa  R.  (2005)  37  Cal.4
th
 
156). 
